(266, 2, '2018-05-23 13:03:16', '2018-05-23 13:03:16', '<em>By Kevin Laudadio</em>\r\n\r\nThe word that comes to mind when I think about Tony’s cancer surgeries is <span style=\"font-style: normal !msorm;\"><em>Family</em></span>. The first time we all gathered at MD Anderson was for his kidney surgery, back in 2013, and the waiting room of the hospital resembled one of our many family reunions: parents, aunts, uncles, cousins, friends, and our honorary family priest. We ate, talked, laughed, and prayed, maintaining an outwardly positive attitude all the while secretly terrified that the doctors would come out with some sort of unexpected news. Fortunately, that didn’t happen, and before long I was hosting Tony and his then 3-year old daughter and 8-months pregnant wife at my place for several weeks during his post-op recovery.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_268\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"241\"]<img class=\"wp-image-268 size-medium\" src=\"http://tonyfoundation.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Tony-Kevin-kids-sized-241x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"241\" height=\"300\" /> The young brothers: Tony (left) and Kevin[/caption]\r\n\r\nIt is a very surreal thing, dealing with a family member’s cancer.  There’s the daily frenzy: doctor’s appointments, meals, kids, insurance. Then there’s the sort of slow burn, the worry, the dread, the unnamed feeling in the pit of your stomach that never quite goes away.  Family was the support that got me through those days, and I’d wager that it’s also what got Tony and Carrie through them, too.  Helping with a precocious 3-year old, trying to only have “organic” food in the house, shopping for comfortable pillows for Tony so he could sort of sit up in bed; these became my daily tasks. <em>Keep the hands busy so the mind doesn’t overload</em> was our unspoken mantra. And in the back of my mind was always the knowledge that it was a tremendous privilege to be able to help, to be present for such a pivotal moment in Tony’s and his family’s lives. And in circle-of-life fashion, about a month after all this I became an uncle again when Carrie had their second little girl!\r\n\r\nThe second round of cancer was certainly unexpected: a minor seizure at the coffee shop leading to a “let’s-rule-out-the-worst-case-scenario” brain scan, which revealed the worst-case scenario: a brain tumor. Again, Carrie was 8 months pregnant, this time with two little ones running around, and the feelings of worry and dread redoubled. Again, family was the lifeline.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_269\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"wp-image-269 size-medium\" src=\"http://tonyfoundation.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/waiting-room-sized-300x246.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"246\" /> In the waiting room at MD Anderson Cancer Center[/caption]\r\n\r\nThe crowd at the hospital for the brain surgery was even larger than two years prior. In true Laudadio fashion, food, laughter, and prayer got us through the almost 10-hour surgery. It was a bit surreal, sitting in the waiting room, knowing that just yards down the hall Tony was awake while doctors opened his skull and removed as much of the tumor as they safely could. When Carrie came out from visiting him after the procedure, it was a great relief to hear “he feels good”! Again, roughly a month after the surgery, the family grew again when Carrie delivered a beautiful little girl. There’s certainly no correlation, but I figure we’re good to go in the cancer department as long as Carrie avoids being 8-months pregnant!\r\n\r\nI’ll wrap up here with a statement that is familiar to everyone reading: Cancer Sucks. Renal cancer, brain cancer, breast cancer, skin cancer — all cancer sucks. I was so excited when Tony envisioned and then created this foundation to help families going through the same experience as ours. First, watching how dedicated and excited he is about the Tony Foundation is awesome. He’s the most energetic I’ve seen him in years!  Second, but no less vital, the opportunity to affect change in even a single family’s experience is a gift. Family is what got us through our journey so far, and the Tony Foundation envisions a way for us to provide that support to other families going through difficult and challenging times.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_270\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"245\"]<img class=\"wp-image-270 size-medium\" src=\"http://tonyfoundation.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/Tony-brothers-sized-245x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"245\" height=\"300\" /> Tony in recovery at MD Anderson after surgery for brain cancer, with brothers Cary (center) and Kevin (right)[/caption]\r\n\r\nThere are several ways you can lend your support as a valued member of our Tony Foundation family, from signing up for <a href=\"http://tonyfoundation.org/subscribe\">email updates,</a> liking our <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/tonyfoundation\">Facebook page,</a> and sharing <a href=\"http://tonyfoundation.org/subscribe\">TonyFoundation.org</a> with your friends and colleagues. And <a href=\"http://tonyfoundation.org/donate\">donate,</a> if you are able. Large or small, every donation brings us closer to helping families in need.\r\n\r\nThis is a chance for us to become part of a collective good, helping out our human family as we deal with adversity.\r\n\r\nGod Bless,\r\n\r\nKevin Laudadio', 'Cancer Sucks: A Brother\'s Perspective', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'open', '', 'cancer-sucks-a-brothers-perspective', '', '', '2018-05-23 21:43:41', '2018-05-23 21:43:41', '', 0, 'http://tonyfoundation.org/?p=266', 0, 'post', '', 0),
